articles.headline: Earthquakes Are Jolting the Netherlands. Gas Drilling Is to Blame.
articles.snippet: Tremors from extraction are blighting 350 square miles. Thousands of homeowners claim damage, and production will end in 2022.
articles.abstract: Tremors from extraction are blighting 350 square miles. Thousands of homeowners claim damage, and production will end in 2022.
articles.lead_paragraph: GRONINGEN, the Netherlands — Driving through fields of low-lying Dutch farmland you pass an occasional odd cluster of silvery pipes and tanks. They are the only visible sign that deep below this northeast corner of the Netherlands is one of the world’s largest natural gas fields.

articles.headline: After 15 Years, Dream Mall Finally Becomes a Reality
articles.snippet: The $5 billion development in the Meadowlands, formerly known as Xanadu and now called American Dream, will open on Friday. Sort of.
articles.abstract: The $5 billion development in the Meadowlands, formerly known as Xanadu and now called American Dream, will open on Friday. Sort of.
articles.lead_paragraph: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. — It has taken 15 years, three owners, two names and hundreds of millions of dollars worth of taxpayer incentives, but a giant mall built on a former swamp in the Meadowlands — and less than 10 miles away from the shopping haven of Manhattan — is finally opening on Friday.
articles.byline: By Michael Corkery and Sapna Maheshwari

articles.headline: ‘It’s Definitely Pretty Empty’: Why Saving WeWork Will Be Hard
articles.snippet: While expanding at a breakneck pace, the co-working company has struggled to turn a profit on millions of square feet of office space.
articles.abstract: While expanding at a breakneck pace, the co-working company has struggled to turn a profit on millions of square feet of office space.
articles.lead_paragraph: Even as WeWork was scrambling to secure a financial bailout last week, Sebastian Gunningham, one of its co-chief executives, made time to oversee the opening of Dock 72, an immaculate shiplike building on the Brooklyn waterfront that houses one of the company’s newest shared working spaces.

articles.headline: Justice Dept. Is Said to Open Criminal Inquiry Into Its Own Russia Investigation
articles.snippet: The move is likely to open the attorney general to accusations that he is trying to deliver a political victory for President Trump.
articles.abstract: The move is likely to open the attorney general to accusations that he is trying to deliver a political victory for President Trump.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For more than two years, President Trump has repeatedly attacked the Russia investigation, portraying it as a hoax and illegal even months after the special counsel closed it. Now, Mr. Trump’s own Justice Department has opened a criminal investigation into how it all began.
articles.byline: By Katie Benner and Adam Goldman

articles.headline: Pentagon, With an Eye on China, Pushes for Help From American Tech
articles.snippet: Talks over how U.S. companies can ensure future supplies of advanced computer chips have taken on more urgency.
articles.abstract: Talks over how U.S. companies can ensure future supplies of advanced computer chips have taken on more urgency.
articles.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Pentagon officials have been holding private discussions with tech industry executives to wrestle with a key question: how to ensure future supplies of the advanced computer chips needed to retain America’s military edge.

articles.headline: Alyssa Milano, Celebrity Activist for the Celebrity Presidential Age
articles.snippet: The actress is trying to stay just famous enough to still get invited to Washington.
articles.abstract: The actress is trying to stay just famous enough to still get invited to Washington.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Alyssa Milano was on Capitol Hill in a floral dress and black Dr. Martens combat boots, her hair pulled into a tight bun atop her head. This is the look — the bun and the boots — that her best friend, Alaa Khaled, says signals to him that “we’re in for something.”

articles.headline: George Soros Has Enemies. He’s Fine With That.
articles.snippet: In an interview, Mr. Soros explained why he thinks the tide is turning back to “globalists” like him and what might happen in the 2020 election.
articles.abstract: In an interview, Mr. Soros explained why he thinks the tide is turning back to “globalists” like him and what might happen in the 2020 election.
articles.lead_paragraph: George Soros is a billionaire philanthropist, a former currency trader, a liberal champion and — in certain circles — a boogeyman. That last label seems to be a badge of honor.

articles.headline: Are the Suburbs Turning Democratic?
articles.snippet: The political dividing line in America used to be between Democratic cities and Republican suburbs. Now it runs through the center of the suburbs themselves.
articles.abstract: The political dividing line in America used to be between Democratic cities and Republican suburbs. Now it runs through the center of the suburbs themselves.
articles.lead_paragraph: EAST GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. — Dave Levitt became a Republican after getting his M.B.A. in 1990. Like him, Republicans valued fiscal conservatism, balanced budgets and free trade, “all the things you learn in business school that are good and help people,” Mr. Levitt said.
articles.byline: By Sabrina Tavernise, Robert Gebeloff and Christopher Lee

articles.headline: G.M. Workers Approve Contract and End U.A.W. Strike
articles.snippet: After the voting by 49,000 members of the United Auto Workers, operations could start to resume Saturday.
articles.abstract: After the voting by 49,000 members of the United Auto Workers, operations could start to resume Saturday.
articles.lead_paragraph: The longest nationwide strike against General Motors in half a century ended on Friday after a solid majority of the company’s union members delivered their support for the four-year contract hammered out by their leaders.
